<h2>HVAC Systems in Nevada</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Nevada's diverse climate zones require carefully selected HVAC systems to handle extreme temperature variations efficiently. Southern Nevada, including Las Vegas and Henderson, experiences a hot desert climate with summer temperatures regularly exceeding 110¬∞F and cooling degree days averaging 3,200-3,600 annually. This intense heat load demands high-efficiency air conditioning systems with SEER ratings of 16-20 or higher to manage electricity costs effectively. Northern Nevada, including Reno and Carson City, faces a semi-arid climate with both significant cooling and heating requirements, necessitating versatile heat pump systems or dual-fuel configurations.</p>

<p>The state's low humidity levels, typically ranging from 10-30%, create unique opportunities for evaporative cooling systems in appropriate applications, though traditional refrigerated air conditioning remains necessary for optimal comfort during peak summer months. High-efficiency variable speed systems perform exceptionally well in Nevada's climate, as they can modulate output to match the dramatic temperature swings between day and night, often exceeding 30¬∞F difference. For optimal performance in Nevada, HVAC systems should include enhanced filtration to handle dust and particulates common in desert environments, along with robust outdoor units designed to withstand intense UV exposure and temperature extremes.</p>

