<h2>Nevada Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Nevada offers a comprehensive array of incentives and rebates that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations, making these energy improvements highly attractive financial investments. The foundation of Nevada's solar incentive structure is the federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, with no cap on the credit amount. Nevada residents can claim this credit on their federal tax return, and any unused credit can be carried forward to subsequent tax years.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> Available through 2032, this credit covers 30% of total solar system costs including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. For a typical \$25,000 system, this represents \$7,500 in direct tax savings. The credit steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations, making current installations particularly valuable.</li>
<li><strong>Nevada Property Tax Abatement:</strong> The state provides a complete abatement of property taxes on the added value of renewable energy systems for new construction and retrofits. This means homeowners won't pay additional property taxes on the increased home value created by solar installations, typically saving \$200-500 annually depending on local tax rates and system size.</li>
<li><strong>NV Energy Net Metering:</strong> NV Energy customers can participate in net metering programs that credit excess solar production at retail rates during peak production hours. The current net metering schedule provides credits of 95% of retail rates for the first 15 years, declining to 88% thereafter, still providing substantial value for solar production that exceeds immediate consumption needs.</li>
<li><strong>NV Energy Rebates:</strong> The utility offers various rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, typically ranging from \$300-1,500 for qualifying heat pumps, air conditioners, and smart thermostats. Additional rebates are available for comprehensive home energy efficiency upgrades when combined with HVAC improvements.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Municipal utilities like those serving Henderson and Boulder City often provide additional rebates and incentives beyond NV Energy programs, including expedited permitting, reduced connection fees, and bonus rebates for combined solar and efficiency upgrades.</li>
</ul>

